text:
i used to dread sparring. i felt self-conscious in this gear, with my pitiful punches and kicks on display for everyone to see. it felt easier to stand there with a self-deprecating attitude and tell all of my opponents that i didnâ€™t know what i was doing, because admitting my ineptitude was easier than dealing with my failure. but iâ€™ve learned something over the past few months. itâ€™s not about looking cool or badass or even winning. itâ€™s about sharpening my instincts and reflexes and putting into practice all i have learned for the sole purpose of defending myself. on the mat, there is no distinction between men and women, adults and children, healthy and injured. the color of the belt you are wearing doesnâ€™t matter. i tell my daughters, â€œiâ€™m not your mother, iâ€™m an evil person who is trying to kidnap you. donâ€™t let me take you.â€ i tell my other partners, â€œdonâ€™t hold back. make me work for this.â€ and i tell myself, â€œthatâ€™s not your training partner. thatâ€™s someone who is intent on hurting you. give him hell.â€
.
.
.

text:
in the words of my fellow warrior woman, "just continue to be your own champion." a few years ago i hit an intense period of self growth, which meant i was falling apart: physically, mentally, spiritually, you name it. my dear friend @theonceuponahorsegirl said this to me one night...and it changed my life. â€¢
to which i add:
keep writing your own story. keep cutting your own path with the tender flesh of your toes. don't stop when the snow breaks, the rocks cut, and the vines pull you onto your knees. be your own hero. stop only when your heart is fully stilled. some days we have to fight and others we must wait in silence. continue to champion your own life, this life.
â€¢
right now is also a time of huge growth and change for me. like an earthquake. luckily, this time, i have support and my own self is a stronger rock by which to dwell upon. be the champions of your own lives goddesses. be the person you need when this life becomes a torrent. you can make it through. #bellamundobirth #bellamundoliving #selfcare #youarethestorm #youarethecalm #warriorwomen #goddesses #growth #change #strength #metoo #beyourownchampion

text:
well.. i just sat down and looked at my memories from today and was smacked in the face with the realization that today is the 7th anniversary of my rape. and today i am celebrating.
because a while ago i read that every 7 years all of the cells in your body replace themselves. so i now have a body untouched by that douche. 
but i am also celebrating cause as much shit as that caused me, its made me the feminist i am. today i wear whatever feels right, today i don't feel ashamed wearing, doing, or demanding certain things. 
today i am mentally healthy.
that shit shook me for years but here i am today. and thats something.

text:
submission is open for the social curator national essay writing competition.â €
â €
â €
this is good news for writers! the social curator national essay writing competition is creating a platform for young scholars to express their views and inculcate superior writing skills. on that note, social curators is pleased to organize the national essay competition 2018-2019.â €
â €
â €
d.k joshi, a renowned environmentalist and social activist established social curators.â €
â €
â €
social curators is a non-government organization devoted towards the welfare, development & protection of the environment, nation and society. hence, all the members and volunteers of the organization are working tirelessly for continuity of the works of late d.k. joshi.â €
â €
â €
eligibility:â €
this competition is open to students from all colleges (graduate/undergraduate) & schools in india. multiple essays from the same college are permitted.â €
â € â €
essay topics/theme:â €
failure of legal machinery and emergence of #metoo movement,â €
â €
â €
transformative constitutionalism and the subrimala judgement, andâ €
â €
sustainable development in india & around the worldâ € â €
â €
prizes:â €
all the participants would be given e-certificates under the banner of â€˜social curatorsâ€™. â €
â €
â €
a cash prize of rs. 5100 to winner and runner-up rs2100.â €
â €
â €
submission guidelines:â €
â €
all participants must send electronic copies of their essays in pdf formats by email to socialcurator4@gmail.com under the subject, â€œentry for essay competitionâ€â €
â €
â €
the participants are also required to send a scanned copy of their institutional identity card and registration fees transaction along with the submission.â €
â €
â €
a total of 4 attachments (essay in pdf, cover letter, id card and registration fees transaction copy) are required with every mail.â €
â €
â €
entrance fee: rs. 250.â €
â €
deadline: 31/1/ 2019.â €
â €
contact info:â €
for more details, contact pulkit joshi, on 9780361242, 7973767217,  or send a mail to socialcurator4@gmail.comâ €

text:
we beat ourselves up for not being better parents to ourselves essentially. 
life keeps moving. i don't mean run out to chase that dollar i mean rest and follow your dreams. #selfcare #forgiveyourself and start gathering the means to a healthier you. you deserve all the love and abundance. there is no lack on mother earth except the limitations we place on each other and ourselves. don't measure your karma with others..."how come i can't travel" "why am i not famous, married..." etc etc etc etc 
what is meant for you comes in. get through this part, break the cycle and move on to the next chapter. 
i love you ğŸ’—ğŸ˜š .
.

text:
cw: discussion of sexual violence against black girls and women 
it is courageous and important to speak truth to power. abusers are abusers, no matter how much fame they attain or how talented they are. the work that black women creatives, organizers, activists, advocates, and survivors have put into uplifting this issue is inspiring and commendable. #survivingrkelly is a necessary and timely conversation in the era of #metoo that deeply resonates with the work that we do at misssey, given that a majority of the youth we serve are black girls who have been impacted by commercial and non-commercial sexual exploitation and abuse. we must listen to and support their stories. 
surviving r. kelly is a three-part docuseries airing on lifetime that covers the allegations of sexual abuse and exploitation of black girls and women that have followed the musician since his rise to fame. you can watch the remainder of the series premiere tonight and tomorrow night. please consider following the #survivingrkelly hashtag on twitter as well for some important dialogue and commentary on racialized sexual violence against black women and girlsâ€”but make sure to take care of yourselves too!

text:
entering my first art exhibition = a nice way to end the whirlwind thatâ€™s been 2018 âœ¨

entitled â€˜narrative threadâ€™, the piece of embroidery was created in response to the brief â€˜take back the narrativeâ€™ and combined some life drawing with continuous line drawing. (see pretentious/ ott description below). .
.
.

a narrative is a portrait, an accumulation of decisions, feelings and events. we tell â€˜narratives of selfâ€™ everyday, recounting our own stories in different ways, giving snapshots and fragments of the best and worst bits to our friends, family and colleagues either face-to-face or via social media. i wanted to reflect this with my piece, with the strong and empowered portrait of the female body being made up of individual stitches, or â€˜fragmentsâ€™ to form a coherent and continuous whole, or visual narrative.

everyone has their own story to tell, an idea which became overwhelmingly apparent in 2018 with women speaking out and recounting their stories in order to affect change. female speech, influence and experience was an overwhelming feature in both the news and media, illustrating to the world that women are rising, more empowered than ever, reclaiming their narratives. take any number of instances: the #metoo movement, hannah gadsbyâ€™s nanette, christine blasey-fordâ€™s testimony or the timeâ€™s up movement (to name a few), it is clear to see that women, in reclaiming their own narratives are redefining female identity both personally and collectively. 
#illustration #lineart #minimalist #feministart #drawing #embroidery #embroideryart

still, it was his much older teenage sons who were the real predators. my first explicit remembrance of abuse (one in which i can recall the entire ordeal vs. bit and pieces) is at around age five or six. he was one of my â€œuncleâ€™sâ€ 18/19 year old sons (he may have been 16 or 17â€¦.he was damn sure old enough to know his private parts didnâ€™t belong anywhere near a five year old child). the saddest thing that sticks out about that memory is i could see my adopted dad walking up the streetâ€¦that didnâ€™t stop my â€œcousinâ€ though. i remember him rushing me so he could â€œfinishâ€ before my dad made it up the driveway. he did too.

people will say why didnâ€™t you say anythingâ€¦i was fucking fiveâ€¦and how does a five year old explain what was done to her when she doesnâ€™t even know what it is? i knew it wasnâ€™t good, i knew that wasnâ€™t a gotdamned lollipop dangling from his body like he said... visit the link in my bio to read the rest. #blackwriters #blackpoets #blackmystics #metoo #survivingrkelly

text:
my revolution begins in the body
it isnâ€™t waiting anymore
my revolution does not need approval or permission
it happens because it has to happen in each neighborhood, village, city or town
at gatherings of tribes, fellow students, women at the market, on the bus
it may be gradual and soft
it may be spontaneous and loud
it may be happening already
it may be found in your closet, your drawers, your gut, your legs, your multiplying cells
in the naked mouth of taut nipples and overflowing breasts
my revolution is swelling from the insatiable drumming between my legs
my revolution is willing to die for this
my revolution is ready to live big
my revolution is overthrowing the state
of mind called patriarchy
my revolution will not be choreographed although it begins with a few familiar steps.
my revolution is not violent but it does not shy away from the dangerous edges where fierce displays of resistance tumble into something new

my revolution is in this body
in these hips atrophied by misogyny
in this jaw wired mute by hunger and atrocity
my revolution is
connection not consumption
passion not profit
orgasm not ownership
my revolution is of the earth and will come from her
for her, because of her
it understands that every time we frack or drill
or burn or violate the layers of her sacredness
we violate the soul of our future
my revolution is not ashamed to press my body down
on her mud floor in front
banyan, cypress, pine, kalyaan, oak, chestnut, mulberry
redwood, sycamore trees
to bow shamelessly to shocking yellow birds and rose blue setting skies, heart exploding purple bouganvillea and aqua sea
my revolution gladly kisses the feet of mothers and nurses and servers and cleaners and nannies
and healers and all who are life and give life
my revolution is on its knees
on my knees to every holy thing
and to those who carry empire-made burdens in and on their heads and backs and
hearts
my revolution demands abandon
expects the original
relies on trouble makers, anarchists, poets, shamans, seers, sexual explorers
tricksters, mystic travelers, tightrope walkers and those who go too far and feel
too much,

text:
since that pissing video i've muted #rkelly and exited a lot of dance floors while marveling at unconscious (though intellectual) women who remained.

im still numb that it took the #metoo movement and a fucking documentary for so many to wake up!

too many of us are sleep waking, operating like zombies and not paying attention, thus have been dumbed-down to not even flinch at things that chip away at our worth. even if you've not had a r. kelly type experience,  you've likely had a situation where you've surrendered a part (or parts) of yourself.

it's no wonder many who know their professional value, have little self-worth.

text:
i do see hope in the new year dawning with saturn cazimi: even lead can be melted down given enough heat, flowing into new shapes and forms, while the dross floats to the top, ready to be observed and held to the light. the dark of the moon has always felt menstrual to me, heightening the potential for release, catharsis, and purification. itâ€™s as if the universe has lined things up so we can enter the gates of tomorrowâ€™s solar eclipse with our vessels emptied, ready to receive something completely new.
.
nevertheless, these have been days tinged with melancholy, if not outright grief. saturn combust, scorched by the rays of the sun, reminds me of the paintings of greek surrealist giorgio de chirico. his sun-blasted piazzas and streets, emptied of people and bisected by irrational, elongated shadows, haunt the viewer with ominous silence. the near and the far seem to collapse into visions of tensile plasticity, and the sunâ€™s presence is not joyful: it burns, feverishly, into visions of razor-edged chiaroscuro, and never seems to penetrate the buildings.
.
my partner is away with family in england, and iâ€™ve been alone in barcelona intent on making progress with my thesis. instead, iâ€™ve been struggling to process the shock of my parentâ€™s car accident. sleep has been elusive, and the nights have cast long shadows. .
.
nevertheless, the second conjunction of uranus to my natal jupiter perfects today, and the past week has seen a flurry of correspondence with friends over the interwebs. jupiter is in my 11thÂ house of social networks, and uranusâ€™s lighting bolts have seen my closest companions beset by the trauma of severances, often of a shocking nature. what iâ€™ve realized is that weâ€™re in this together: old fears, paranoias, and seemingly intractable grief have surfaced amongst my cohort.
.
so many planets are now in the late degrees of signs, mars sinking a salt-encrusted dagger into the tenderest of wounds. the sun continues to eviscerate us, as if with powdered glass, as we prepare to crawl into the eclipseâ€™s womb, rubbed raw and incandescent. what iâ€™ve realized is that itâ€™s my friendships that will see me through the coming year.
.
(continuedâ¬‡)

text:
more on working at the intersections in program design, legislative priorities, and long range goals, "astho's sexual violence prevention legislative report highlights legislation on adverse childhood experiences (aces) and housing stability as potential areas to address the risk and protective factors of sexual violence. the scan covers the 2018 legislative session and categorizes aces and housing stability legislation by common themes. for aces, the scan produced 75 pieces of legislation from 26 states and the district of columbia. the housing stability scan produced 52 pieces of legislation from 14 states and the district of columbia. overall, states are making strides to address social determinants of health through aces and housing stability legislation. while not expressly focused on sexual violence, innovative solutions to address aces and housing stability may strengthen primary prevention of sexual violence because they target risk and protective factors that are common across issues." #rootcausescommunitysolutions #wechooseallofus
link to full report: http://www.astho.org/generickey/generickeydetails.aspx?contentid=20370&folderid=5156&catid=7203

text:
â€œi used to walk around my suburban neighborhood every morning until i ran into a friendly older guy who wanted to stop and chat. for half an hour. every day. then he wanted to start walking with me. i changed my route to avoid him and i would still run into him. finally i changed my route more drastically to avoid him completely. on the new route i kept running into a younger guy who flirted nonstop. he also wanted me to walk with him, and i did, once, because of course i thought i was supposed to be nice. i wasnâ€™t afraid, but i still made sure he didn't find out where i live. he asked me disturbing questions about how much i love my kids. finally i have up and stopped going for walks. the truth is, i didn't even realize this was harassment until i started reading this account, and even now i feel like the stupid one for not realizing it. it's crazy to me that our society has normalized it so much that we don't even recognize it as wrong until someone tells us it is.â€ â€” shelsy @shelsysketchbook

as i thought my life was ending in the #lasvegasshooting i thought of what kind of imprint i had made on the world thus far.  now i live my life with more #urgency to make a #difference in the lives of others. trying to take focus off of me and giving my efforts and wisdom of lifeâ€™s twists and turns to others.  i am realizing that the tragedy and darker moments in my life are set ups for me to impact others and not be afraid of carving out my own #pathofdreams instead of spectating.
i am starting 2019 working on two projects to #followmydreams âœ¨
a little teaser on the two projects:  i am pitching the idea of a weekly #talkshow and working on an immersive #artgallery based concept and adjacent #bar #restaurant that i will be launching with two business partners in the heart of #sanantonio spring/summer 2019 that will bring much joy to the #texas #community & 32 million plus annual tourists by creating a #familyfriendly experience.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

with ficial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

the simplest description of the plot line goes something like this: president trump isnâ€™t under investigation; he is only pretending to be, as part of a countercoup to restore power to the people after more than a century of governmental control by a globalist cabal. also, there are pedophiles.

a figure named â€œq,â€ who supposedly possesses q-level security clearance, disperses â€œcrumbsâ€ that â€œbakersâ€ bring together to create a â€œdoughâ€ of synthesized information. (this is not how baking works, but that seems the least of our worries.) because q is the 17th letter in the alphabet and 17 is also a number trump has said a few times, among other clearly-not-coincidences, he is the real deal, not an internet troll engaged in an elaborate example of live-action role-play.

thatâ€™s what qanon followers really want, after all. thatâ€™s where their â€œstormâ€ motto comes from. most americans were puzzled when, in a meeting with military leaders months ago, trump said, â€œyou know what this represents? maybe itâ€™s the calm before the storm.â€ but these theorists thought they knew exactly what he was talking about. trump was pointing at the officersâ€™ uniforms.

the storm qanon truthers predict will never strike because the conspiracy that obsesses them doesnâ€™t exist. but while they wait for it, theyâ€™ll try to whip up the winds, and the rest of us will struggle to find shelter. qanon is scary because itâ€™s getting bigger, itâ€™s scary because we donâ€™t know how to stop it, and itâ€™s scary because the people behind it wonâ€™t be stopped, and, until their illusory storm arrives, they wonâ€™t be satisfied.

the washington post

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied. 
in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
i donâ€™t usually make new yearâ€™s resolutions (why wait until next year to do something you want to do now?) but something iâ€™ve been meaning to do for awhile now is return to krav maga more regularly! i know iâ€™m busy, and some classes at work are indeed pretty great, but i would love to do some sharkbait/sparring again!
â€¢
this video is from awhile back - you had to stand there with your eyes closed and someone in a bullet suit would attack you from an unknown direction. it was both terrifying and exhilarating at the same time, but i miss that suit - it was such good practice!
â€¢
i'm still a beginner, but i think i've learned enough by now that i can inflict a bit of damage if i really need to.
i once had a guy who was harassing me at the time, on hearing that i had started learning self defense, lean in uncomfortably close and ask with a sick smile, "should i be worried?"
yes. yes, you should be.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
#teavwatcherz - more women have come forward read article via blavity: in june 2018, writer sil lai abrams accused american television personality and extra tv  host  aj calloway of sexual assault. as blavity previously reported, the domestic violence activist revealed the details of the abuse exclusively to the hollywood reporter.

six months later, two more women have come forward to the daily beast with their own recounts of calloway's malpractice. speaking with the news and pop culture site, abrams revealed that at least 10 women, including herself, have accused calloway of sexual misconduct. 
one accuser, who requested anonymity in her testimony, filed a suit against calloway on december 24 at the west orange police department in new jersey. to maintain the confidentiality of the victim, representatives of the west orange police department declined to offer anymore specifics of the dispute.

the second accuser, who the daily beast dubbed "talia" on the basis of obscurity, believes calloway would attempt to destroy her career if she revealed her identity. "i don't want it to affect my future, everything that i've worked hard forâ€”and aj is someone that would try to do that." talia said she and calloway went to dinner, and following their meal calloway drove the two back to his home for an after-party with a group of friends. once the other guests left for the night, talia recalls calloway forcing himself on her. when she refused, he exposed himself to her. following the incident, talia said calloway promised to drop talia back at her place in the morning. 
despite the allegations against calloway, abrams added that warner brothers television, which produces extra tv, have neglected to speak on their employee's behalf. "i emailed blake bryant, the head of publicity at warner brothers televisionâ€”the same guy who kim masters reached out to when she was working on her piece for the hollywood reporterâ€”asking him why they havenâ€™t issued any statements," abrams explained. "i let him know that i'd spoken with multiple women and there are multiple alleged victims of aj. i was thinking, warner brothers has got to say something, i mean, what are they going to do?

text: one year ago today i got my hair cut for the first time in 3 years. i felt very brave and empowered. it had been 3 years since i was raped by a man who was supposed to just be giving me a haircut in preparation for my new headshots. @kaitmariehair offered to take on the task of helping me work through my ptsd. she had never met me before but reached out to me after i posted in a womenâ€™s group on fb expressing my fear of going to a salon. she made me feel so comfortable during my appointment and i felt right at home in her studio. she let me bring my dog and said i could invite anyone else i wanted. not to mention she gave me the exact cut i wanted! i am so proud of myself for this moment and the many breakdowns iâ€™ve pushed through since. âœŠğŸ¼ #bebrave #rosearmy #metoo #timesup #ptsd #empowerment #hairstyle #haircut #hair #bobhaircut thanks for reminding me of this special moment @ladylucent and for being by my side through that mess of a trial.

text: these photos were taken in the same tree by the same man, the one who was standing here all along!! definitely seems like a lifetime later. the girl on the left looked happy but inside she was dying, suffering and just barely surviving. she wore a smile to hide the pain but now she'll never be the same. she survived because the fire inside her burned stronger than the fire around her!! i'm starting 2019 even stronger than before, i truly believe in miracles, all things are possible!! i never realized how miserable i was and how miserable i made people around me, i was toxic and it impacted every aspect of my life. at 40 years old, i can honestly say i have completely come full circle,  i've let go of the toxic things, the negativity, the miserable people who i allowed to infiltrate my life,  my family and my business. in one year i've been able to reverse the damage of abuse, mental torment and physical neglect and allowed myself to fall in love with the girl that was so unlovable. when you truly embrace forgiveness and live with love in your heart you can literally alter the universe and become the best version of yourself. spread kindness like glitter and be nice to people lezettechristinemua #promua #140poundsgone #followmenow #boxybaddies #selflove #mommyisback #bethebestversionofyou #inspiration #motivation #youtuber #metoo #proteiniskey #bethechange #methemoglobinemia #loveyourself #depressionsucks #lovebodyandsol #embraceyourself #wlsjourney #wlssupport #weightloss #youcandoit #tools #stillfighting #plussize #different #changed

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
2018 has been a roller coaster ride for the oppressed and the oppressor, for the helpless and the powerful and for the campaigners and the bashers. from marital rape to homosexuality to #metoo we have come a long way. let us have a look at some of the most important events that india witnessed this year.

#4 women can now enter sabarimala

another judgment that upheld the fact that â€œdevotion should not be subjected to discriminationâ€. in india, on one hand, we consider women as pure and sacred goddesses while on the other hand, we see them as obnoxious and vile vamps who would break the oath of celibacy of a god. and because of this, women in the reproductive age group were not allowed in the sabarimala temple â€“ to keep the lord ayyapa celibate. this itself was a disrespect to the god whom we are reducing to our own humanly limitations. on top of that, putting the burden of celibacy of a god on women by restricting their entry showed the inherent discrimination against women in supposedly the most liberal religion that worships female gods. stripping the religion of its bigotry definitely helped in uplifting the common consciousness of people. however, considering the mass unrest at sabarimala over the entry of women, there is still a long way to go.

#2018rewind #highlightsof2018 #judgement #womenite #sabarimalaverdict #equalrights #humanrights #devotion #discrimination #equalitytogod

text:
this season, as we step into the new year &, in the tradition of kwanzaa, i honor one of the principles: .
.
.
kuumba.
.
.
 what kuumba health stands for. .
.
.
kuumba means creativity, and encourages us to always do as much as we can, in the way we can, in order to leave our community more beautiful and beneficial than we inherited it. 
i am proud to find creative health solutions, so your vision vs. your stress is front and center. 
thanks for being part of this 2018 ride! i reduced stress & self doubt without losing my edge as a ceo of my wellness company for over a decade, took better care of myself & others like a boss through changes in my personal life where i bend but do not break, and practiced healthy habits that actually works from the board room to the bedroom (without guilt or having to be perfect) - and you can too!
.
.
.

may this year in review, inspires yours to come: 
and in the words inspired by mrs. oprah winfrey. it is time to get busy living your most inspired life. in a world where we are inundated daily with intense headlines, it is more important than ever that we focus on making our dreams our reality. take these 5 steps today:
-declare your dreams
-define your why and how
-celebrate small wins
-get a dream partner
-invest in a well-balanced life...
i am so honored to be a guide and dream partner for you and those you care for to do all the above 5 things & more. 
dm me to clarify your vision for the upcoming year, create a road-map for a healthier you that works (without stress eating, self doubt, or needing to be perfect), so you can manifest your best season yet. cheers to supporting your vision unleashed & stress solutions in 2019 (after #metoo, self doubt, or chronic pain)!

mnÃ¡: i'm so hopeful 2019 will be our year.

in 2018, we repealed the 8th, saw the rise of the #metoo movement, and we saw an avalanche of womenâ€™s voices coming together to bring about change.

personally i took a step back from the online, got out of a long-term relationship and learnt to enjoy my own company again, travelled to the u.s for the first time, and honestly discovered a fire for womenâ€™s right well beyond anything i knew possible.

so, in 2019, i want to:

do anything i can to encourage more women to have the confidence to put themselves forward for leadership. change will only continue if we have feminist voices driving it.

mind my mind. people are arguing about what is and isnâ€™t triggering online but in reality, we can only unfollow anything thatâ€™s no good for us. as the saying goes: â€œwalk away from anything Â that no longer serves you". travel more.

read more - recommendations welcome!

be present. be happy. be focused.

feel free to share your resolutions ğŸ‘€

text:
in my cell phone named "heart" i saved you as a contact called love. i also made a recharge with my feelings and with a strong network of hope i dialed a number to your heart.
i could listen the caller tune which was your heartbeats.
obviously, you picked the call and respected my feelings.
you shared with me your past dialed number.
the one you had saved as love,
the one with whom your connection never failed.
the one with whom you use to talk till dawn.
i use to listen it peacefully. 
but deep down, like the network even my voice use to crack.

i wanted to tell you that i wanted to be in your favourites, in your recently dialed number, your speed dial. but your line always seemed busy
sometimes you did picked up my call only to keep me on hold. i tried to built are connection but it was your past dialed number which was still ringing in your mind.
and here i am dialing the same number in the hope that you will pick the call someday. but in this life it seems: "the number you are trying to call is not reachable"

yours blocked contact,
darshan sanghvi
(@darshansanghvi28)
.
.
.

this really hits home for me. communication with your children is so important anyway but there can be dire consequences for not listening to your children or for your children not feeling comfortable enough to open up to you when it really matters.

listen without judgment, as hard as that may be. agree to disagree. make sure your children are comfortable talking to you about anything, no matter how taboo, uncomfortable or unpopular it may be. and let your kids be who they are. they'll thank you for it later.

this really hits home for me. communication with your children is so important anyway but there can be dire consequences for not listening to your children or for your children not feeling comfortable enough to open up to you when it really matters.

listen without judgment, as hard as that may be. agree to disagree. make sure your children are comfortable talking to you about anything, no matter how taboo, uncomfortable or unpopular it may be. and let your kids be who they are. they'll thank you for it later.

text: r kelly was arrested after the tape of him urinating on a child surfaced. the tape was widely circulated and viewed for sport by many. it took over 5 years for the case to finally go to trial and in the end, he was found not guilty. what stood out for us was the attitude of a juror who was interviewed about the verdict. he said he just didn't believe the girls who testified. he didn't like the way they presented themselves; the way they talked or dressed. now keep in mind, this juror along with the entire courtroom watched this tape and the vile content it contained, and yet this man chose to overlook what he saw and allowed his own personal biases to dictate his vote as to whether justice would finally be served. this means he didn't see the girl in the tape as a child nor a victim, which is often the case when black girls are involved. and, this isn't just true where non-black people are concerned. this is the reality for black girls even where their own family, friends, and other black people are concerned. they are simply not believed; not seen as victims, and generally blamed and shamed for their own abuse. this juror wasn't the only one who failed to bring justice to kelly's victims; every adult who willingly participated in and overlooked the abuse of those girls are also guilty of failing them and every other victim as well. it is the apathy of others that allow predators like r kelly to thrive. people like his assistant whose attitude was "this is just what he was into and it was a daily thing, but we were doing our job". oh and let's not leave out the multitudes who gathered at the court everyday in support of the artist and shamelessly declared support for him while blaming the girls for their abuse. and finally, we have to acknowledge the men and women in the barbershops, hair salons, on the job, in our families, and in our places of worship who saw the little girl on that tape and even the victims they know personally as fast tailed, short skirt wearing, and too grown for their own good. this is why abuse continues to occur! afterall, r kelly was grooming his next victim and flaunting his proclivities in the courtroom and was still found not guilty.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: i remember every detail. the way the air felt. the way the room smelled. they way his hands did what they did. the way my heart pounded. the sound of me feet hitting the floor and what felt like the longest steps i could every take. the crumbling i felt between my fingers. the way i felt when i knew, everything was a lie. when i would begin the hardest chapter in my story. i will continue setting this world on fire. because i know what it feels like to look for the light and to desperately need warmth. #metoo

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
understand, there are countless women, currently living in a house of horror!.
the mind games, the belittling, the abuse, the manipulation, the shame!.
behind every woman, lies a story!.
very few, are strong enough to get out. less known share!.
the life of a woman, is something serious!.
our lineage is strong!.
from the stories of tamar and judah, saartjie (sara)baartman, califia, harriet tubman, madam c.j. walker, angela davis, foxy brown and numerous others!.
our strength reaps!. regain, it queens!.
it's hard.
trust me, i know!.
#mystoryislong #metoo #suvivor  #conqueror

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

footage of nigel farage swigging a pint and thanking steve bannon and breitbart for the brexit result was deleted from a breitbart youtube channel, following the data scandal surrounding cambridge analytica. - well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farageâ€™s nod to steve bannon certainly hasnâ€™t aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analyticaâ€™s influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses peopleâ€™s personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firmâ€™s vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trumpâ€™s campaign to become us president.

anna o'donohue

text:
for so long i have made my healing contingent upon the progress and outcome of my legal case. i have sacrificed my dignity and privacy at every turn with the hope of protection and justice. i have forced myself to say, "you can focus on healing after you get justice." i naively trusted that if i "did everything right," went to the hospital, got a rape kit, reported my rape to the police, told my story clearly and focused on the facts, that i would be believed and action would be taken. instead, i was met with judgement, victim blaming, doubt, and leading questions designed to trick me into downplaying being raped. i have placed my healing in the hands of a system to want a to keep me broken so if they ever call upon me to testify i am just as shattered and scared as i was right after he raped me years later. if you are tearless and factual when reporting than it must have not been that bad. if you finally go numb from describing the same details over and over again for a year, you are apathetic and unconcerned. how is it fair that he gets to continue his life unaffected and i am expected to remain broken in order to be "believable"? does continuing to live despite him trying to break me make me less of a victim? must i be "damaged goods" to be taken seriously? i cannot continue to define my healing based on the responses of the around me. not only did my rapist steal my safety and freedom of choice, but he has robbed me of a year of my life. a time where i should be happy. i am finishing college, i have a long time partner, i am working towards my dream career. how can i continue to let him rob me of my independence, safety and happiness. for so long i have felt like a person who lost a loved one and every time i catch myself smiling, i wonder how on earth i could do that. i was raped and there has been no justice, what do i have to smile about? i need to regain control of the rest of my life and take my healing into my own hands.

leave a ğŸ’“ in the comments if you read this far/can relate to what i am feeling.

text_retweet:
#survivingrkelly #repost @jacquereid
ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ»
r kelly is the tip of the iceberg 
______________
my blood boils whenever i see grown men hitting on or flirting with girls.  and yes, i often step in and let my opinion be known.  because r kelly is just the tip of a horrific and very old iceberg in the black community.
____________
i have been on board with the #muterkelly movement before it existed. i refuse to play or dance to his music as part of my own personal boycott.  for me the final straw was that poor girl in that video tape. first aaliya and then that, was all the proof i needed. but watching #survivingrkelly this week was heartbreaking and infuriating. but what is worse than his disgusting behavior is the fact that so many people, after seeing this docu series, still defend and stand by this predator who victimizes black girls. 
______________
a big part of what drives that defense of r kelly is the belief that itâ€™s ok for black men to be attracted to and have sex with black girls. it has been quietly acceptable for decades and while we know it is wrong, far too many in our communities stay silent. there are countless studies that reveal that up until their very early twenties,  the brains of girls are still developing.  and for teens, sex with an adult can be incredibly harmful because of the power imbalance.  that means these girls are more likely to follow this adults lead when it comes to sex which often leads to unprotected, 
experimental and often violent sex.  these girls are merely objects and are often left with long lasting psychological issues. this has to stop. we have to speak up. we have to let our girls be girls and give them a fighting chance to reach their potential. the world is hard enough for black girls without letting them fall under the control of some pedophile, who wants to play out his sick sexual fantasies and control their minds.
____________
i am all for seeing r kelly brought to justice, but letâ€™s simultaneously focus on figuring out a way to put a stop to the legions of men out there preying on our black girls every single day.  this has to stop. 
#survivingrkellly 
#saveourgirls
#thishastistop 
#pediphila 
#muterkelly
#metoo

text:
as a survivor of sexual violence, i feel obligated and inclined to restore the power imbalances and injustices that i know so well. it took me 15 years to tell my story, fight my internal demons, and confront and make peace with the past. i choose not to share the details of my story here and now in fear of triggering or re-traumatizing othersâ€¦ or maybe iâ€™m just not â€œthereâ€ yet.Â  and we must remember that thatâ€™s ok too. i believe that the metoo campaign has the potential to help create the culture, platforms and dialog needed to combat the shame and self-blame that trap victims in silence for farÂ too long.Â  i am also conscious not to become hyper-focus on where the onus lies as it jeopardizes the â€œmovementâ€ into becoming simply a passing moment. what i have learned by being more open and candid with my experiences is that the details or circumstances of my story is not a rarity. this is not to downplay anyoneâ€™s experiences or trauma but sometimes such details can sensationalize a situation which can distract from the intention of sharing in the first place. for victims of sexual violence, the â€œshock-factorâ€ serves no purpose.Â  i see this in hollywood as others are also finding the courage to come forward and tell their stories. this should all be liberating and empowering, but i canâ€™t help but feel somewhat detached and disconnected from it all when conversations circle around the harvey weinsteins and trumps of the world. iâ€™d like elevate the conversation beyond seeking justice, redemption and/or revenge because this movement cannot center on placing blame or perpetuating fear.Â by sharing our experiences, i hope that future generations can have open discussions surrounding sexual violence.

today's best price:  get it on amazon! joel springâ€™s history of school polices imposed on dominated groups in the united states examines the concept of deculturalizationâ€•the use of schools to strip away family languages and cultures and replace them with those of the dominant group. the focus is on the education of dominated groups forced to become citizens in territories conquered by the u.s., including native americans, enslaved africans, chinese, mexicans, puerto ricans, and hawaiians. in 7 concise, thought-provoking chapters, this analysis and documentation of how education is used to change or eliminate linguistic and cultural traditions in the u.s. looks at the educational, legal, and social construction of race and racism in the united states, emphasizing the various meanings of "equality" that have existed from colonial america to the present. providing a broader perspective for understanding the denial of cultural and linguistic rights in the united states, issues of language, culture, and deculturalization are placed in a global context. the major change in the 8th edition is a new chapter, "global corporate culture and separate but equal," describing how current efforts at deculturalization involve replacing family and personal cultures with a corporate culture to increase worker efficiency. substantiveâ€¦
